Tasks: extract effect sizes (Creativity and Handedness)

Owen Morgan

March 18, 2024

Effect size calculations

Note on coding effect directions: in all analyses, right/strong handers are coded as “1”, mixed/left handers are coded as “0” (and, right/strong handers are coded as “n1”/“m1”…, mixed/left handers are “n2”/m2”…).

Bosch 2013 (TTCT-F)

Bosch, J. (2013). Prenatal testosterone, hemispheric dominance and looseness of associations [PhD Thesis]. Universitätsbibliothek Graz.

51 participants (whatever handedness, measured with the EHI) completed the AUT (modified - one response per item) and TTCT.They do not report any relevant results for the AUT. For the TTCT, they report simple correlation coefficients for Figural Originality (.04), Verbal Originality (.19), and Verbal Fluency (.00). All estimates favor right handers, or neither.

Coren 1995 (AUT)

Coren, S. (1995). Differences in Divergent Thinking as a Function of Handedness and Sex. The American Journal of Psychology, 108(3), 311. https://doi.org/10.2307/1422892

The AUT was scored only on fluency, the number of responses that each person came up with:

“n, divergent thinking measures have been presumed to be measures of creativity. One of the most popular of these tests is the Alternate Uses Test, where subjects are required to find novel uses for common objects. The variant used in this study was Form A (Christensen, Guilford, Merrifield, & Wilson, 1960). It consists of three parts, each of which contains three common items (e.g., a shoe) and space for up to six alternative uses per item. Each part is timed at 4 min. The score is simply the number of novel uses for each item that the participant generates.”

The Authors report means and SD for men and women, for each of four handedness groups. However, they do not report n for each group (except for men and women), which makes it impossible to aggregate means and SDs exactly.

For analysis, assume equal in each handedness group, and calculate overall means/SDs for right vs. left, strong vs. mixed handers.

study <- "coren_1995"

handedness_measure <- "LPI"

assume_n <- input %>%
  filter(handedness != "all") %>%
  mutate(n = case_when(
                       handedness == "strong_right" & sex == "m" ~ 58,

                       handedness == "mixed_left"   & sex == "m" ~ 58,

                       handedness == "strong_right" & sex == "f" ~ 82,
                       handedness == "mixed_right"  & sex == "f" ~ 81,
                       handedness == "mixed_left"   & sex == "f" ~ 81,
                       handedness == "strong_left"  & sex == "f" ~ 81
                       )
)

Calculate group means, SDs, for each handedness group, collapsing across sex. Store this data in a new table, and save to a file: “data/proc/…proc_1.csv”

proc_1 <- tibble::tibble(n = numeric(),
                         handedness = factor(),
                         mean = numeric(),
                         sd = numeric()
                         )

## Define function to calculate stats for each handedness group, across sex
## Input: n, handedness group, input data for coren_1995_AUT
## Return: a tibble row with columns n, handedness, mean, sd
## Depends on: tibble, lib/util.R
stats_across_sex <- function(data, h_grp) {
  ## x1 is coded for males, x2 for females
  m1 <- data %>% filter(handedness == h_grp & sex == "m") %>% .[["mean"]]
  m2 <- data %>% filter(handedness == h_grp & sex == "f") %>% .[["mean"]]
  n1 <- data %>% filter(handedness == h_grp & sex == "m") %>% .[["n"]]
  n2 <- data %>% filter(handedness == h_grp & sex == "f") %>% .[["n"]]
  sd1 <- data %>% filter(handedness == h_grp & sex == "m") %>% .[["sd"]]
  sd2 <- data %>% filter(handedness == h_grp & sex == "f") %>% .[["sd"]]

  stats_row <- tibble::tibble(n = n1 + n2,
                     handedness = h_grp,
                     mean = agg_mean_cochrane(m1 = m1, m2 = m2, n1 = n1, n2 = n2),
                     sd = agg_sd_cochrane(m1 = m1, m2 = m2, n1 = n1, n2 = n2,
                                           sd1 = sd1, sd2 = sd2)
                     )

  return(stats_row)
}

h_grps <- unique(assume_n[["handedness"]])
for (j in 1:length(h_grps)) {
  stats_row <- stats_across_sex(assume_n, h_grps[[j]])
  proc_1 <- proc_1 %>% add_row(stats_row)
}

write_csv(proc_1, here(extract_dir, "data", "proc", str_c(study, "_", task, "_proc_1.csv")))

## Define function to calculate stats across handedness groups
## Input: proc_1, handedness groups to collapse, label for new group
## Return: a tibble row with columns n, handedness, mean, sd
## Depends on: tibble, lib/util.R
stats_across_h_grps <- function(proc_1, h_grps, h_grp_new) {

  n1 <- proc_1 %>% filter(handedness == h_grps[[1]]) %>% .[["n"]]
  n2 <- proc_1 %>% filter(handedness == h_grps[[2]]) %>% .[["n"]]
  m1 <- proc_1 %>% filter(handedness == h_grps[[1]]) %>% .[["mean"]]
  m2 <- proc_1 %>% filter(handedness == h_grps[[2]]) %>% .[["mean"]]
  sd1 <- proc_1 %>% filter(handedness == h_grps[[1]]) %>% .[["sd"]]
  sd2 <- proc_1 %>% filter(handedness == h_grps[[2]]) %>% .[["sd"]]

  stats_row <- tibble::tibble(n = n1 + n2,
                          handedness = h_grp_new,
                          mean = agg_mean_cochrane(m1 = m1, m2 = m2, n1 = n1, n2 = n2),
                          sd = agg_sd_cochrane(m1 = m1, m2 = m2, n1 = n1, n2 = n2,
                                               sd1 = sd1, sd2 = sd2)
  )
  return(stats_row)
}

Falletta, B. A. (1986). The relationship between sinistrality and right cerebral hemisphere cognitive functions in a select sample of college students. Florida Atlantic University.

Data are extracted from Table 7 (p. 73). 28 left and right handers (measured by self-reported “hand used most of the time”) were scored on originality and elaboration on the Figural Torrance test (pictural construction). Originality: The point estimate favors right handers slightly. [L: 4.5714 (2.284, SE=.432) vs. R: 4.750 (1.974, SE=.373) ]

Feen et al. 2020 (AUT)

Feen, F. E., Zickert, N., Groothuis, T. G. G., & Geuze, R. H. (2020). Does hand skill asymmetry relate to creativity, developmental and health issues and aggression as markers of fitness? Laterality, 25(1), 53–86. https://doi.org/10.1080/1357650X.2019.1619750

For the AUT, subjects were all asked: “Within two minutes, enter as many uses for a book that you can think of.”

Fluency: the number of valid answers.

“Combined” (In Zickert et al. 2019, this is called “Originality”): unique answers were divided into ten bins, from the 10% most common to the 10% least common. Each answer received an integer score from 1 (most common) to 10 (least common/most original). These were summed for each person.

“Originality” divide originality score by the number of valid answers. (As described in the main text, this variable was called “Originality/fluency” in Zickert et al., 2019).

From the main text: “Finally, we calculated three divergent thinking scores per participant: a fluency score, which was the amount of valid answers given; a combined score, which was the sum of the originality scores; and an originality score, which was the average originality score per valid answer. The details of the calculation and analysis can be found in Appendix 3.” Appendix 3 contradicts the main text as to how the AUT scores are named: “…for each participant we calculated the individual fluency score by counting the number of valid answers and the originality score by adding the creativity scores of the valid answers.” For analysis, I assume that the “combined” score represents Originality (sum)/Fluency, following the appendix.

The authors report inferential stats for each score, and for principle components, one of which included: Originality, Fluency, Combined, and something called “Artistic–questionnaire”, which was different from “Artistic–self assessment.” I infer that “Artistic–self assessment” was the slider scale response to the question “How artistically creative are you?” Zickert et al., 2019 explain two Artistic creativity scores: 1. “Artistic creativity self-assessment”: ??? 1. “Artistic creativity score”: sum of likert responses to how often participants do different creative activites. [0 - 30]

For each AUT score, the authors report an F-test, a p-value, and a beta value, as well as an Overall R^2, for a model including five regressors: Asymmetry score, Asymmetry score squared, Sex, Age, and Age squared. (Table 4) For meta-analysis, the beta coefficients for Originality, Fluency, and “Combined” are extracted (because the beta coefficient is from a mixed model, it cannot be pooled with other studies).

Felton 2017 (RAT)

Felton, A. (2017). Interhemispheric Interaction and Creativity. [PhD Dissertation]

Group means and SDs are reported for strong and mixed handers, defined by a median split on the absolute value of EHI handedness (70 in each group, based on df = 140 for two-sample t-test).

For percent correct (“Accuracy”), reported numbers do not add up. Based on the means and SDs, there is a large, significant mixedy advantage (t = 3.8). But, the authors report a low t-value, 0.45. (And, SDs are extremely tight, compared to other RAT studies with similar sample size. For example, see Turner 2016). Could there be a typo in the table? I believe that most likely explanation is that the author accidentally presented SEM instead of SD: assuming this and calculating the true SD yields the reported t-value of 0.45.

Folley 2006 (AUT)

Jones et al. 2011 (AUT)

Jones, T., Caulfield, L., Wilkinson, D., & Weller, L. (2011). The Relationship Between Nonclinical Schizotypy and Handedness on Divergent and Convergent Creative Problem-Solving Tasks. Creativity Research Journal, 23(3), 222–228. https://doi.org/10.1080/10400419.2011.595964

“…handedness was not a significant predictor of divergent thinking, beta = .38, t = 1.29, p > 0.05.” [“divergent thinking” = AUT]

“…handedness was not a significant predictor of convergent thinking, beta = 1.46, t = 0.95, p > 0.05.” [“convergent thinking” = RAT]

Means, ns, and sd for each handedness group (split by an irrelevant second grouping) are also reported. Because effect size can be calculated from these values without covariates (in the regression analysis, schitzotypy), I will use the effect size calculated from group means instead.

Only fluency was reported, for this reason: “Fluency alone was used in the current study since this has been shown to be informative of divergent thinking (Bately & Furnham, 2008; Kyriacou & Brugger, 2003)”

Note that schizotypy is overrepresented among the left handers in this sample.

study <- "jones_2011"
task <- "AUT"
handedness_measure <- "EHI"
rl_sm <- "R/L"
es_type = "d"
measure <- "Fluency"
## AUT ("divergent thinking")
## Lefties
m_left_low <- 12.80
sd_left_low <- 12.97
n_left_low <- 5
m_left_high <- 22.63
sd_left_high <- 8.34
n_left_high <- 16

m_left <- agg_mean_cochrane(n1 = n_left_low,   n2 = n_left_high,
                            m1 = m_left_low,   m2 = m_left_high)
sd_left <- agg_sd_cochrane(sd1 = sd_left_low, sd2 = sd_left_high,
                            n1 = n_left_low,   n2 = n_left_high,
                            m1 = m_left_low,   m2 = m_left_high)
n_left <- n_left_low + n_left_high

## Righties
m_right_low <- 14.15
sd_right_low <- 9.42
n_right_low <- 27
m_right_high <- 15.56
sd_right_high <- 7.28
n_right_high <- 16

m_right <- agg_mean_cochrane(n1 = n_right_low,   n2 = n_right_high,
                             m1 = m_right_low,   m2 = m_right_high)
sd_right <- agg_sd_cochrane(sd1 = sd_right_low, sd2 = sd_right_high,
                             n1 = n_right_low,   n2 = n_right_high,
                             m1 = m_right_low,   m2 = m_right_high)
n_right <- n_right_low + n_right_high

d <- msd_to_d(m1 = m_right, sd1 = sd_right,
                      m2 = m_left, sd2 = sd_left)

esci <- psych::cohen.d.ci(d = d, n1 = n_right, n2 = n_left, alpha = .05) %>%
  as_tibble()

es <- es %>%
  add_row(study = study, task = task, measure = measure, es_type = es_type,
          lower = esci$lower, effect = esci$effect, upper = esci$upper,
          n1 = n_right, n2 = n_left,
          h = handedness_measure, rl_sm = rl_sm,
          notes = "From Ms, SDs, Ns (Aggregated)",
          include = 1
          )

Katz 1980 (RAT)

Katz, A. N. (1980). Do Left-Handers Tend to Be More Creative? The Journal of Creative Behavior, 14(4), 271–271. https://doi.org/10.1002/j.2162-6057.1980.tb00262.x

Katz reported: (a) ” The two handedness groups did not differ on any of the measures of creativity.” and (b) Pearson’s rho for degree of right handedness and TTCT subscores.

“Pearson product-moment correlations between the degree of handedness and creativity test scores also failed to find a relationship. The correlations with each test were as follows: Torrance Verbal: -.019 (Fluency)…”

Direction of correlation is not reported explicitly. I assume that a positive correlation means that stronger right handedness corresponds to higher creativity scores because:

  1. Higher handedness scores are for stronger right handedness (“Scores could range from 18 (most strongly left-handed) to, 162 (most strongly right·handed).”)

  2. In several other papers I have looked at, a positive score on the TTCT is a better score.

Turner 2016 (RAT)

Turner, C. E. (2016). Do saccadic bilateral eye movement enhance performance on creative tasks? [PhD Thesis]

The authors report the result of an F-test for a main effect of handedness on “total problems solved with insight”: F(1, 86) = 4.23, p < 0.05. Subjects were instructed to report, after every RAT problem, if they experienced an “aha” feeling. Out of the total number of RAT problems solved in 5 minutes, those with a reported “aha” counted as “problems solved with insight”.

The authors report the means and SDs for total problems solved (a more direct, or at least more common measure of divergent thinking), in a table. These group means and SDs are for two experimental groups, in two saccade conditions that are irrelevant for our purposes. For meta-analysis, whole group means are extracted from this table to find an effect size for the effect of handedness on total RAT problems solved in 5 minutes.

## Is it possible to estimate an effect combining the two conditions?
## The number of participants in each condition should be equal (24 in each group)
## Following Claire's suggestion, I will take the mean of means, and pool SD:
## "i think you could square each SD, multiply by N - 1 for each, sum the resulting values, then divide by the new N-1 and square root? (basically reversing the SD formula.)"
measure  <- "Total problems solved in 5 minutes"
n1 <- 24
n2 <- 24

## pool sd, following Claire's formula
## Subtract one from the pooled n to calculate aggregated sd --
## subtracting two creates "pooled sd", which estimates a population sd based on the sample sds (rather than calculating the sample sd, if the two groups were combined)
pool_sd <- function(sd1, sd2, n1, n2) {
  sd <- sqrt( ((sd1^2)*(n1-1) + (sd2^2)*(n2-1)) / (n1 + n2 - 1) )
  return(sd)
}
## pool sd, following statology.com
pool_sd_statology <- function(sd1, sd2, n1, n2) {
  sd <- sqrt( ((sd1^2)*(n1-1) + (sd2^2)*(n2-1)) / (n1 + n2 - 2) )
  return(sd)
}

## Construct aggregate sd, following wikipedia's formula for aggregated sample-based sd
## https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pooled_variance
## I used this before finding an equivalent formula int he Cochrane handbook
agg_sd <- function(sd1, sd2, n1, n2, m1, m2) {
  m_agg <- (1/(n1+n2)) * (n1*m1 + n2*m2)
  sd <- sqrt(
             ( (n1-1)*sd1^2 + n1*m1^2 + (n2-1)*sd2^2 + n2*m2^2 - (n1+n2)*m_agg^2 )
             / (n1 + n2 - 1)
  )
  return(sd)
}

sd_mixed_overall <- pool_sd(sd1 = sd_mixed_central, sd2 = sd_mixed_moving,
                            n1 = n1, n2 = n2)
sd_strong_overall <- pool_sd(sd1 = sd_strong_central, sd2 = sd_strong_moving,
                            n1 = n1, n2 = n2)
m_mixed_overall <- mean(m_mixed_central, m_mixed_moving)
m_strong_overall <- mean(m_strong_central, m_strong_moving)

d_overall <- msd_to_d(m1 = m_strong_overall, sd1 = sd_strong_overall,
                     m2 = m_mixed_overall, sd2 = sd_mixed_overall)

esci <- psych::cohen.d.ci(d = d_overall, n1 = n1, n2 = n2, alpha = .05) %>%
  as_tibble()

This effect size is in the same ballpark but not identical to the estimate from the F-test (ES= 0.424, CI = [0.013, 0.831]. This may be because the number of subjects in each condition is not reported clearly, or because a covariate such as condition was included in the reported F-test.

To get around this uncertainty, I will reconstruct sample SD using the Cochrane Handbook’s formula, and use that to calculate Cohen’s D. This is more likely to reflect the effect size of interest than relying on the authors’ F-test result, which might have included covariates or adjustments.

Turner 2017 (RAT)

Turner, C. E., Hahn, M. E., & Kellogg, R. T. (2017). Semantic processing in the left versus right cerebral hemispheres following unilateral hand contractions. Laterality: Asymmetries of Body, Brain and Cognition, 22(2), 219–232. https://doi.org/10.1080/1357650X.2016.1154861

The study reports this result for the correlation between EHI score and RAT score (number of problems answered correctly in 15 minutes) “We also examined whether the laterality quotients of participants were related to task performance. Scores of above 75–80 indicate strong right handedness and in the vast majority of cases, LH dominance. The laterality quotient was not reliably related to remote associate scores (r = .07).”

The formula for “r” was not reported. I will presume that it is a Pearson correlation coefficient, because this is standard when correlated continuous variables (EHI and RAT scores are both ordinal scores with many levels, which might be treated as continuous). Because none were reported, I will assume that no covariates were included in this correlation analysis.

There were 60 participants total: 43 strong right, 17 non-right handers.

Shobe et al. 2009 (AUT)

Shobe, E. R., Ross, N. M., & Fleck, J. I. (2009). Influence of handedness and bilateral eye movements on creativity. Brain and Cognition, 71(3), 204–214. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.bandc.2009.08.017

Task details: “An adaptation of the Alternate Uses Test (Chamorro-Premuzic, 2006) was used to measure creativity. This adaptation consisted of 20 common items (e.g. paper-clip, pencil, shoe, for full list see Appendix A). We used 15 items from the original Alternate Uses Test (Christensen et al., 1960) and five from a common word bank (Snodgrass & Vanderwart, 1980)”

AUT scoring: “Responses on the Alternate Uses Test were scored on five differ- ent sub-scores: (a) fluency, indicated by the total number of uses listed per item (regardless of ‘quality’ or appropriateness); (b) originality, indicated by the number of responses provided by 0–5% pf participants (3 points), 6–10% (2 points) or 11–15% (1 point) of all participants in the sample; (c) amount of detail or elaboration provided for each use (on a 0–5 point scale); (d) flexibility or the num- ber of ‘categorically’ distinct answers (1 point for each distinct ‘category’ of uses); and (e) appropriateness or usefulness of responses (1 point for each ‘appropriate’ response).”

Handedness measure: “Handedness was measured using a modification of the Edinburgh Handedness Inventory (Oldfield, 1971), an instrument shown to be reliable and well-validated (Bryden, 1977). Partici- pants were asked to indicate their preference (always, usually, no preference) of hand use for 10 activities from the Edinburgh Handedness Inventory (e.g., writing, drawing, throwing). Handedness scores for each participant ranged from 100 (perfectly right- handed) to 100 (perfectly left-handed).”

To make handedness groups, they took a median split on EHI (-100, +100; median 77.5), and excluded the one strong left hander (-100). This made two groups: 30 mixed handers, 32 right handers.

All participants were assigned randomly into one of two groups: control or eye movement. Because the eye movement condition may influence AUT performance, the control condition is most relevant for the present analysis. Unfortunately, the exact n by handedness group in the control condition isn’t known (we know the totals for each condition (30 and 32), and for each handedness group (30 and 32), but not for each handedness group in each condition). Equal n’s in each handedness group are impossible, and the only mathematical restriction is that there are the same number of strong righty controls and mixedy eye movers.

For this control condition, we have group means, F-values with df. Cohen’s D can be calculated from the F values, if we assume that group n’s are roughly equal. This assumption seems reasonable, and is made here for effect extraction.

The exact n is known for the overall group comparison (collapsing across control and eye movement conditions). The direction of all effects is the same as in the control condition. For this less relevant (to meta-analysis) comparison, one could calculate an exact value for Cohen’s D.

Stewart & Clayson 1980 (TTCT-F)

Stewart, C. A., & Clayson, D. (1980). A Note on Change in Creativity by Handedness Over A Maturational Time Period. The Journal of Psychology, 104(1–2), 39–42. https://doi.org/10.1080/00223980.1980.12062947

TTCT-F Scores: Originality, Elaboration, Flexibility, and Fluency, and a Total score, which is the mean of the four subscores.

The authors report: 1. For Total score, Originality, and Elaboration, the results of an F-test for a model including handedness and age as IVs, and total creativity score (mean of the four subscores) as the DV. For Flexibility and Fluency, this test is reported as “No significant effect” of handedness. 1. For all subscores, each handedness group’s mean. 1. For Total score, a graph showing group means and an unlabeled error bar.

For analysis, Cohen’s D is extracted for the Reported F-tests, and the missing test results are marked as “unreported” (coded as NA). (The difference in means for both unreported tests trends in the same direction as the reported tests).

Zickert et al. 2018 (AUT)

Zickert, N., Geuze, R. H., van der Feen, F. E., & Groothuis, T. G. G. (2018). Fitness costs and benefits associated with hand preference in humans: A large internet study in a Dutch sample. Evolution and Human Behavior, 39(2), 235–248. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.evolhumbehav.2018.01.001

The authors report linear and quadratic models of the effect of EHI handedness (binned by Strong Left, Moderate Left, Ambidextrous, Moderate Right, Strong Right) on divergent thinking (with covariates). They also provided raw data, which can be used to construct simple correlation and group difference statistics.

For the AUT, subjects were all asked: “Within two minutes, enter as many uses for a book that you can think of.”

Fluency: the number of valid answers. Originality: unique answers were divided into ten bins, from the 10% most common to the 10% least common. Each answer received an integer score from 1 (most common) to 10 (least common/most original). These were summed for each person. “Originality per fluency”: divide originality score by the number of valid answers.

Linear model fits for the effect of handedness direction on each subscore are shown in table 4. For each divergent thinking measure, n = 9089 (Only 9089 of ~20k participants completed this section of the questionnaire).

AUT scores are also reported in a GLM analysis as a factor that includes all three scores. “For artistic creativity (PC 2 creativity) there is only a linear effect of hand preference with a small effect size and a qua- dratic but very small effect of age (Fig. 4b, Tables 4 and 6).”

The authors report eta^2 and n for the effect of handedness on each AUT score. Partial rho exracted from eta squared can be reported in a separate table/section from other studies: “Partial effect sizes should not be combined with bivariate correlations, nor should different types of partial effect sizes be combined. Meta-analysts should present two sets of analyses: one for bivariate correlations and one for partial effects. For an example, see Aloe and Becker (2009).” (Aloe & Thompson, 2014)

Per Lakens 2013, 90% CI should be used for partial eta^2 to compare with 95% CI on Cohen’s D or rho, because F-tests are always one-sided.

Raw data are available and can be used to find simple rho and Cohen’s D for R/L and S/M handedness. These effect sizes should be used in meta-analysis because they enable pooling with other studies.

#### Clean the data

## Authors' exclusions:

# - had missing data on any of the questions that were used in the statistical analysis and were not optional (except for the number of children as this question was added to the questionnaire in a later stage of the project). 
# - did not specify their sex as male or female. 
# - were under the age of 15 years and over 100 years. 
# - indicated that they have a temporary or permanent limitation in one oftheirarmsorhands. 
# - gave nonsensical answers (e.g. being 20 years old having three grandchildren).

## Remove rows that readr could not parse
problem_rows <- problems(raw_data) |> pull(row)
proc <- raw_data |> 
  slice(-problem_rows) |> 
## Apply authors' exclusions
  filter(
  `filter_$` =="Selected"
)


## Create an asymmetry score based on raw EHI values
proc <- proc |> 
  mutate(EHI_abs = abs(EHIscore))

## Create categorical handedness variables
proc <- proc |> mutate(
  handedness_rl = case_when(EHIscore > 0 ~ "right",
                            EHIscore <= 0 ~ "left"),
  handedness_sm = case_when(
    EHIscore %in% c(-20, 20) ~ "strong",
    EHIscore < 20 & EHIscore > -20 ~ "mixed"
  ),
    handedness_rml = factor(
    case_when(
      handedness_rl == "right" &
        handedness_sm == "strong" ~ "strong right",
      handedness_rl == "right" &
        handedness_sm == "mixed" ~ "mixed",
      handedness_rl == "left" &
        handedness_sm == "mixed" ~ "mixed",
      handedness_rl == "left" &
        handedness_sm == "strong" ~ "strong left"
    ),
    levels = c("strong left", "mixed", "strong right")
  ),
  handedness_rmml = factor(
    case_when(
      handedness_rl == "right" &
        handedness_sm == "strong" ~ "strong right",
      handedness_rl == "right" &
        handedness_sm == "mixed" ~ "mixed right",
      handedness_rl == "left" &
        handedness_sm == "mixed" ~ "mixed left",
      handedness_rl == "left" &
        handedness_sm == "strong" ~ "strong left"
    ),
    levels = c("strong left", "mixed left", "mixed right", "strong right")
  ),
  handedness_3q = santoku::chop_equally(
    proc$EHIscore, groups = 4, labels = c("Left", "Mixed", "Right")),
  handedness_rl_median = case_when(
    EHIscore > median(EHIscore) ~ "right",
    EHIscore <= median(EHIscore) ~ "left"),
  handedness_sm_median = case_when(
    EHI_abs >= median(EHI_abs) ~ "strong",
    EHI_abs < median(EHI_abs) ~ "mixed")
)

S/M

Fluency (rho)

Because of the imbalanced n between strong left and right handers, a simple correlation test cannot distinguish between an effect of strong handedness, and an effect of left handedness.

We can undersample left handers and then run the correlation test, but a significant correlation may still be driven by a large effect of direction of handedness.

Undersample left handers. (Randomly select 1316 from each handedness group).

set.seed(123)
undersample_strong_left <- proc |> 
  filter(handedness_rmml == "strong left") |> 
  slice_sample(n = 1316, replace = F)

set.seed(123)
undersample_mixed_left <- proc |> 
  filter(handedness_rmml == "mixed left") |> 
  slice_sample(n = 1316, replace = F)

set.seed(123)
undersample_mixed_right <- proc |> 
  filter(handedness_rmml == "mixed right") |> 
  slice_sample(n = 1316, replace = F)

set.seed(123)
strong_right <- proc |> 
  filter(handedness_rmml == "strong right") |> 
  slice_sample(n = 1316, replace = F)

proc_undersampled <- bind_rows(
  undersample_strong_left,

If we don’t undersample, we see a stronger “mixed hand advantage”, driven by low scores from lefties.

study <- "zickert_2018"

Effect sizes and confidence intervals are rounded to the 3rd decimal, with trailing zeroes removed.
